Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and finely dice @Yellow Onion{1}(peeled and finely diced) until you have
¾ cup (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings). Drain @Black Beans{1} over a small #bowl{},
reserving liquid.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%tsp} in a large #pot over medium-high heat.
Add onion; cook, stirring, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp}; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @Tex-Mex Paste{1}; cook until slightly darkened in color, ~{1%minute}.

Pat @Chicken Breast Strips{10%oz} dry with paper towels. Once onion is softened,
add chicken to pot; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring frequently,
until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} for chicken. Cook through the
rest of this step as instructed.

> Beef alternative: Cook beef until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir @Mushroom Stock Concentrate{2}, beans, half the @Crushed Tomatoes{13.76%oz},
1 cup water, and ¼ cup reserved bean liquid into pot. (For 4 servings, use all
the crushed tomatoes, 2 cups water, and ½ cup bean liquid.) Bring to a boil and
cook, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{5-8%minutes}.

> TIP: Prefer your broth a bit thicker? Simmer a little longer—or simmer a
> little less if you prefer a thinner broth! You're the chef, after all.

Taste and season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Crush a few @Blue Corn Tortilla Chips{1.5%oz}.

Divide soup between #bowls{} and top with @White Cheddar Cheese{1/2%cup},
@Smoky Red Pepper Crema{2%tbsp}, and as many crushed tortilla chips as you like.

> TIP: Start with a few crushed chips and add more as you go to keep them crunchy!
> Serve with whole tortilla chips on the side.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.